It is a segmentation model that intends to predict whether delinquent clients will eventually pay on their own, or if they will need collection agents to track them down. The hope is that this will reduce the costs related to collection. We don't know much about the model, or the implementation that's currently running inside AWS because when the project was handed off from the old consultancy company to Kyndryl they never provided us with the keys to the VM. The model was originally a single huge 800 line R script that collected three different datasets (CLIE, POLA, and HFAC [clients, policies, and invoices]), did some initial transformations to each dataset, merge them in this monstrosity of ~240 features, and +10M records with all kinds of datatypes, performed some additional ETL, did some feature engineering, trained the models on the go (No MLOPs whatsoever). Spat out some files that were later used for clustering, and reporting. We migrated that logic to python initially. Then the Data Engineering team took care of most of the initial ETL (just up before the feature engineering) and the current scripts take it from there, performing some last column derivations that I forgot to send to the DE team, and it now runs on Sagemaker pipelines. Caleb's intention was to make it conform to best practices, have it's own IaC, have it thoroughly documented, change the configs from json to yml, and essentially refactor it once again into the "best practices" the AI thought at that time were the best way to organize the code.\cb1 \
